I've found comprehensive information about OpenSearch hybrid search query structure. Here are the key findings:

## Hybrid Query Structure

You can use a hybrid query to combine relevance scores from multiple queries into one score for a given document. A hybrid query contains a list of one or more queries and independently calculates document scores at the shard level for each subquery.

## Query Example with BM25 and Neural Sub-queries

A hybrid query combines two query clauses—a neural query and a match query, and specifies the search pipeline as a query parameter. Here's a concrete example:

```
GET /my-nlp-index/_search?search_pipeline=nlp-search-pipeline
{
  "_source": { "exclude": [ "passage_embedding" ] },
  "query": {
    "hybrid": {
      "queries": [
        {
          "match": {
            "passage_text": {
              "query": "Hi world"
            }
          }
        },
        {
          "neural": {
            "passage_embedding": {
              "query_text": "Hi world",
              "model_id": "aVeif4oB5Vm0Tdw8zYO2",
              "k": 5
            }
          }
        }
      ]
    }
  }
}
```

## Search Pipeline Configuration

The normalization-processor uses the min_max normalization technique and the arithmetic_mean combination technique, assigning a weight of 30% to the first query and 70% to the second query.

Example search pipeline:
```
PUT /_search/pipeline/nlp-search-pipeline
{
  "description": "Post processor for hybrid search",
  "phase_results_processors": [
    {
      "normalization-processor": {
        "normalization": {
          "technique": "min_max"
        },
        "combination": {
          "technique": "arithmetic_mean",
          "parameters": {
            "weights": [ 0.3, 0.7 ]
          }
        }
      }
    }
  ]
}
```

The `search_pipeline` parameter in the query URL enables the pipeline to normalize and combine the document scores from both the BM25 (match) and neural sub-queries.


